		<p class="section-headers__new-section" id="tips-and-tricks">
			<span><i class="fa fa-paper-plane fa-lg"></i> Tips and Tricks</span>
		</p>
		<p class="page-design__our-experience">
			<ul class="page-design__our-experience--list">
				<li>
					<strong>Pablo Escobar -</strong> you may think that Escobar is very interesting and find that you want to ask a lot of questions about it. You need to remember that Escobar was killed in 1993, which means that most of these Colombians lived through the terror. Someone we met compared it to the Holocaust where that’s a part of Germany’s history. Here, they are still recovering from it and it is something they are trying to get over. Colombian have also been trying to create tourism and a good name for their amazing country. Please be aware that <strong>this is still fresh for them</strong> so do not walk around the streets speaking his name. One of our tour guides in Medellin pointed out that since most Colombians can’t speak English, they will just hear his name and not know what context you are speaking about him in and assume the worst. Just be conscious. 
				</li>
				<li>
					Although the security has risen in the last little while you need to <strong>be extra careful in Colombia</strong>, especially big cities like Medellin. We heard stories of large groups of people getting mugged at 7pm outside their hostel. Best advice is to only bring what you need with you and just comply with the demands of any muggers. 
				</li> 
				<li>
					You'll see lots of cigarette and candy vendors walking around. Hint: they sell MUCH more than candy and cigarettes.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong> When to Visit - always!</strong> But try and avoid tourist season which is December to February where the prices will be higher. 
				</li> 
				<li>
					<strong> Take flights between cities that are far apart -</strong> The flights are very cheap in Colombia! The main airline used in Colombia is called VivaColombia, and they are both affordable and offer great service. We original were going to take a bus from Medellin to Santa Marta but quickly changed our minds. The bus would have taken at least 16 hours and goes through a potentially dangerous windy path for ~20 CAD. The flight is 1h 10min for 50 CAD. Completely worth it. We wish AirCanada had the same values...  
				</ul>
			</p>
